BVD-SOLANA-PDA-004	Shared PDA Across Users	Program Derived Addresses shared across multiple users instead of being user-specific, creating unauthorized access and state collision vulnerabilities. When PDAs are not properly scoped to individual users or resources, different users can access or modify each other's data.	program-derived-address	medium	\N	\N	A01:2021	{"description": "Design PDA seeds to ensure proper isolation between users and resources. Include user public keys in seeds for user-specific PDAs.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Global PDA shared by all users\\nlet (config_pda, _) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[b\\"config\\"],  // All users share this!\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// All users can modify the same config\\nlet config = Config::load(config_pda)?;\\nconfig.value = new_value;\\n\\n// SECURE: User-specific PDAs\\nlet (user_config_pda, _) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[\\n        b\\"config\\",\\n        user.key().as_ref(),  // Unique per user\\n    ],\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// Each user has their own config\\nlet config = Config::load(user_config_pda)?;\\nconfig.value = new_value;\\n\\n// SECURE: Resource-specific PDAs\\nlet (escrow_pda, _) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[\\n        b\\"escrow\\",\\n        seller.key().as_ref(),\\n        buyer.key().as_ref(),\\n        mint.key().as_ref(),\\n    ],\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with proper scoping\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct InitializeUserAccount<'info> {\\n    #[account(\\n        init,\\n        payer = user,\\n        space = 8 + UserAccount::INIT_SPACE,\\n        seeds = [\\n            b\\"user-account\\",\\n            user.key().as_ref(),  // User-specific\\n        ],\\n        bump\\n    )]\\n    pub user_account: Account<'info, UserAccount>,\\n    #[account(mut)]\\n    pub user: Signer<'info>,\\n    pub system_program: Program<'info, System>,\\n}\\n\\n#[account]\\npub struct UserAccount {\\n    pub bump: u8,\\n    pub owner: Pubkey,\\n    pub balance: u64,\\n}"}	[]	["https://www.anchor-lang.com/docs/pdas#pda-sharing", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/calling-between-programs#program-derived-addresses"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.538851+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.010485+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-TYP-002	Struct Layout Compatibility Confusion	Type confusion where two structs with compatible memory layouts but different semantics are used interchangeably. Even with discriminator checks, structs with identical field types in the same order can be confused, leading to misinterpretation of data fields and unauthorized access.	type-safety	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use unique discriminators for all account types, even those with similar layouts. Validate both discriminator and account owner. Use type-safe wrappers and explicit type annotations.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Structs with same layout\\n#[derive(BorshDeserialize, BorshSerialize)]\\npub struct TokenVault {\\n    pub mint: Pubkey,         // 32 bytes\\n    pub authority: Pubkey,    // 32 bytes\\n    pub amount: u64,          // 8 bytes\\n}\\n\\n#[derive(BorshDeserialize, BorshSerialize)]\\npub struct EscrowAccount {\\n    pub seller: Pubkey,       // 32 bytes  \\n    pub buyer: Pubkey,        // 32 bytes\\n    pub price: u64,           // 8 bytes\\n}\\n\\n// Both have identical layout! Can be confused without discriminators.\\n\\npub fn withdraw_from_vault(vault: &AccountInfo) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // If attacker passes EscrowAccount:\\n    // - mint becomes seller\\n    // - authority becomes buyer\\n    // - amount becomes price\\n    let vault = TokenVault::try_from_slice(&vault.data.borrow())?;\\n    \\n    // Check passes with wrong account type!\\n    if vault.authority == expected_authority {\\n        transfer_tokens(vault.amount)?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Add discriminators and unique identifiers\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[account]\\npub struct TokenVault {\\n    pub discriminator: [u8; 8],  // Unique discriminator\\n    pub vault_type: VaultType,   // Additional type identifier\\n    pub mint: Pubkey,\\n    pub authority: Pubkey,\\n    pub amount: u64,\\n}\\n\\n#[account]\\npub struct EscrowAccount {\\n    pub discriminator: [u8; 8],  // Different discriminator\\n    pub escrow_id: u64,          // Unique identifier\\n    pub seller: Pubkey,\\n    pub buyer: Pubkey,\\n    pub price: u64,\\n}\\n\\n#[derive(AnchorDeserialize, AnchorSerialize, PartialEq)]\\npub enum VaultType {\\n    Token,\\n    NFT,\\n    LP,\\n}\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct WithdrawFromVault<'info> {\\n    #[account(\\n        mut,\\n        has_one = authority,\\n        constraint = vault.vault_type == VaultType::Token @ ErrorCode::InvalidVaultType\\n    )]\\n    pub vault: Account<'info, TokenVault>,\\n    pub authority: Signer<'info>,\\n}\\n\\npub fn withdraw_from_vault(ctx: Context<WithdrawFromVault>) -> Result<()> {\\n    // vault is guaranteed to be TokenVault with correct type\\n    let vault = &ctx.accounts.vault;\\n    transfer_tokens(vault.amount)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/type-layout.html", "https://www.anchor-lang.com/docs/space"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.558001+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.037673+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-LOG-005	Incorrect Token Amount Calculations	Flawed calculations involving token amounts, particularly when handling different decimal precisions, conversions between token units, or fee deductions. Token math errors can lead to incorrect balances, lost funds, or unauthorized minting.	logic-errors	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Always account for token decimals when converting between UI amounts and raw amounts. Use checked arithmetic for all token calculations. Validate amounts before and after conversions.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Ignoring token decimals\\npub fn transfer_tokens(\\n    amount_ui: u64,  // User inputs \\"100 USDC\\"\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // USDC has 6 decimals, should be 100_000_000 not 100!\\n    transfer(amount_ui)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Incorrect decimal conversion\\npub fn convert_to_raw_amount(ui_amount: u64, decimals: u8) -> u64 {\\n    // Overflow if decimals large!\\n    ui_amount * 10_u64.pow(decimals as u32)\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Fee calculation with precision loss\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_bps: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Division before multiplication loses precision\\n    (amount / 10000) * fee_bps\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Token amount comparison without decimal alignment\\npub fn compare_amounts(\\n    token_a_amount: u64,  // 6 decimals (USDC)\\n    token_b_amount: u64,  // 9 decimals (SOL)\\n) -> bool {\\n    // Comparing incompatible decimal amounts!\\n    token_a_amount > token_b_amount\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Proper decimal handling\\npub fn transfer_tokens_with_decimals(\\n    amount_ui: u64,\\n    decimals: u8,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // Convert UI amount to raw amount\\n    let multiplier = 10_u64\\n        .checked_pow(decimals as u32)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    amount_ui\\n        .checked_mul(multiplier)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Safe decimal conversion\\npub fn ui_amount_to_raw(\\n    ui_amount: u64,\\n    decimals: u8,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    if decimals > 18 {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument);\\n    }\\n    \\n    let power = 10_u64\\n        .checked_pow(decimals as u32)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    ui_amount\\n        .checked_mul(power)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\npub fn raw_amount_to_ui(\\n    raw_amount: u64,\\n    decimals: u8,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    let divisor = 10_u64\\n        .checked_pow(decimals as u32)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    raw_amount\\n        .checked_div(divisor)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Fee calculation with correct precision\\npub fn calculate_fee_precise(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    fee_bps: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // Multiply first, then divide (preserves precision)\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_bps)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(10000))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Amount after fee deduction\\npub fn amount_after_fee(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    fee_bps: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    let fee = calculate_fee_precise(amount, fee_bps)?;\\n    \\n    amount\\n        .checked_sub(fee)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with SPL Token\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\nuse anchor_spl::token::{self, Token, TokenAccount, Mint};\\n\\npub fn transfer_with_fee(\\n    ctx: Context<TransferWithFee>,\\n    amount_ui: u64,\\n) -> Result<()> {\\n    let mint = &ctx.accounts.mint;\\n    let decimals = mint.decimals;\\n    \\n    // Convert UI amount to raw\\n    let amount_raw = ui_amount_to_raw(amount_ui, decimals)?;\\n    \\n    // Calculate fee (in raw amount)\\n    const FEE_BPS: u64 = 30;  // 0.3%\\n    let fee = calculate_fee_precise(amount_raw, FEE_BPS)?;\\n    \\n    let amount_after_fee = amount_raw\\n        .checked_sub(fee)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::InsufficientAmount))?;\\n    \\n    // Transfer using SPL Token\\n    token::transfer(\\n        CpiContext::new(\\n            ctx.accounts.token_program.to_account_info(),\\n            token::Transfer {\\n                from: ctx.accounts.from.to_account_info(),\\n                to: ctx.accounts.to.to_account_info(),\\n                authority: ctx.accounts.authority.to_account_info(),\\n            },\\n        ),\\n        amount_after_fee,\\n    )?;\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct TransferWithFee<'info> {\\n    #[account(mut)]\\n    pub from: Account<'info, TokenAccount>,\\n    #[account(mut)]\\n    pub to: Account<'info, TokenAccount>,\\n    pub mint: Account<'info, Mint>,\\n    pub authority: Signer<'info>,\\n    pub token_program: Program<'info, Token>,\\n}"}	[]	["https://spl.solana.com/token", "https://docs.rs/spl-token/latest/spl_token/"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.582121+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.060632+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-INT-006	Integer Multiplication Overflow	Multiplication operations that risk numeric overflow without proper checking. In Solana programs, unchecked multiplication is particularly dangerous as products grow exponentially and can easily exceed u64::MAX. This commonly occurs in token calculations with decimal conversions, fee calculations, and compound interest formulas.	arithmetic	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use checked_mul() for all multiplication operations. Be especially careful with token decimal conversions and fee calculations where multiplication is common.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unchecked multiplication\\npub fn convert_tokens(amount: u64, rate: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Can easily overflow!\\n    amount * rate\\n}\\n\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_bps: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Overflow before division\\n    (amount * fee_bps) / 10000\\n}\\n\\npub fn compound_interest(principal: u64, rate: u64, periods: u32) -> u64 {\\n    // Repeated multiplication causes overflow\\n    let mut result = principal;\\n    for _ in 0..periods {\\n        result = result * rate / 100;\\n    }\\n    result\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Checked multiplication\\npub fn convert_tokens(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    rate: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(rate)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\npub fn calculate_fee(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    fee_bps: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_bps)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(10000))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\npub fn compound_interest(\\n    principal: u64,\\n    rate: u64,\\n    periods: u32,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    let mut result = principal;\\n    \\n    for _ in 0..periods {\\n        result = result\\n            .checked_mul(rate)\\n            .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(100))\\n            .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    }\\n    \\n    Ok(result)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn calculate_token_amount(\\n    ctx: Context<CalculateAmount>,\\n    base_amount: u64,\\n    multiplier: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64> {\\n    base_amount\\n        .checked_mul(multiplier)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Safe decimal conversion\\npub fn ui_to_raw_amount(\\n    ui_amount: u64,\\n    decimals: u8,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    let power = 10_u64\\n        .checked_pow(decimals as u32)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::InvalidArgument)?;\\n    \\n    ui_amount\\n        .checked_mul(power)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#integer-overflow", "https://docs.rs/solana-program/latest/solana_program/macro.checked_mul.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.588208+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.069226+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-INT-007	Integer Division Overflow	Division operations that may overflow in edge cases, particularly when dividing minimum integer values by -1. While less common than addition or multiplication overflow, division overflow can occur with signed integers and cause unexpected panics or incorrect results. In unsigned arithmetic, this pattern also catches potential division by zero which causes panics.	arithmetic	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use checked_div() for all division operations to handle both overflow and division by zero. Always validate divisors are non-zero before division.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unchecked division\\npub fn calculate_average(total: u64, count: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Panics if count == 0\\n    total / count\\n}\\n\\npub fn distribute_equally(amount: u64, recipients: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // No validation\\n    amount / recipients\\n}\\n\\npub fn calculate_ratio(numerator: i64, denominator: i64) -> i64 {\\n    // Can overflow with i64::MIN / -1\\n    numerator / denominator\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Checked division\\npub fn calculate_average(\\n    total: u64,\\n    count: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    total\\n        .checked_div(count)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::InvalidArgument)\\n}\\n\\npub fn distribute_equally(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    recipients: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    if recipients == 0 {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument);\\n    }\\n    \\n    Ok(amount / recipients)\\n}\\n\\npub fn calculate_ratio(\\n    numerator: i64,\\n    denominator: i64,\\n) -> Result<i64, ProgramError> {\\n    numerator\\n        .checked_div(denominator)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn calculate_share(\\n    ctx: Context<CalculateShare>,\\n    total_amount: u64,\\n    share_count: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64> {\\n    require!(share_count > 0, ErrorCode::InvalidShareCount);\\n    \\n    total_amount\\n        .checked_div(share_count)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::DivisionError))\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Division with validation\\npub fn safe_divide(\\n    numerator: u64,\\n    denominator: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    if denominator == 0 {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // checked_div still protects against edge cases\\n    numerator\\n        .checked_div(denominator)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Division with default\\npub fn calculate_average_or_zero(\\n    total: u64,\\n    count: u64,\\n) -> u64 {\\n    if count == 0 {\\n        return 0;\\n    }\\n    total / count\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#integer-overflow", "https://docs.rs/solana-program/latest/solana_program/macro.checked_div.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.591272+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.073114+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-SEC-001	Malicious Transaction Simulation	Programs that simulate transactions or perform operations based on simulated results without proper validation. Transaction simulation in Solana is meant for testing and pre-flight checks, not for making security decisions. Programs that rely on simulation results can be manipulated by attackers who provide fake simulation data or manipulate simulation parameters.	security	high	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Never use simulation results for security decisions or authorization checks. Simulations should only be used off-chain for UI/UX purposes. All security checks must be performed on-chain during actual transaction execution.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Using simulation for authorization\\nuse solana_client::rpc_client::RpcClient;\\nuse solana_sdk::transaction::Transaction;\\n\\npub fn authorize_transaction(\\n    client: &RpcClient,\\n    transaction: &Transaction,\\n) -> Result<bool, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {\\n    // Simulating transaction to check if it would succeed\\n    let simulation = client.simulate_transaction(transaction)?;\\n    \\n    // DANGEROUS: Making security decision based on simulation!\\n    if simulation.value.err.is_none() {\\n        // Attacker can manipulate simulation results\\n        return Ok(true);\\n    }\\n    Ok(false)\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Accepting simulated account data\\npub fn process_with_simulation(\\n    account_data: &[u8],\\n    is_simulated: bool,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    if is_simulated {\\n        // Skip validation for simulated data - DANGEROUS!\\n        return process_account(account_data);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // Only validate real transactions\\n    validate_account(account_data)?;\\n    process_account(account_data)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Simulation only for UI/estimates\\nuse solana_client::rpc_client::RpcClient;\\nuse solana_sdk::transaction::Transaction;\\n\\n// Off-chain code for UI\\npub async fn estimate_transaction_cost(\\n    client: &RpcClient,\\n    transaction: &Transaction,\\n) -> Result<u64, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {\\n    // Simulation is OK for estimates, not authorization\\n    let simulation = client.simulate_transaction(transaction)?;\\n    \\n    // Use simulation only for displaying estimate to user\\n    let cost = simulation.value.units_consumed.unwrap_or(0);\\n    Ok(cost)\\n}\\n\\n// On-chain code - never check if simulated\\npub fn process_instruction(\\n    program_id: &Pubkey,\\n    accounts: &[AccountInfo],\\n    instruction_data: &[u8],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // ALWAYS validate, regardless of simulation\\n    validate_accounts(accounts)?;\\n    validate_instruction_data(instruction_data)?;\\n    \\n    // All security checks performed on-chain\\n    let account = &accounts[0];\\n    if !account.is_signer {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::MissingRequiredSignature);\\n    }\\n    \\n    if account.owner != program_id {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::IncorrectProgramId);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // Process with full validation\\n    process_validated_instruction(accounts, instruction_data)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor (no simulation bypass)\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[program]\\npub mod my_program {\\n    use super::*;\\n    \\n    pub fn process_transaction(\\n        ctx: Context<ProcessTransaction>,\\n        amount: u64,\\n    ) -> Result<()> {\\n        // Anchor ALWAYS validates:\\n        // - Account discriminators\\n        // - Account ownership\\n        // - Signer requirements\\n        // - Custom constraints\\n        // \\n        // No way to bypass via simulation\\n        \\n        let account = &mut ctx.accounts.user_account;\\n        \\n        // All checks performed on-chain\\n        require!(\\n            account.balance >= amount,\\n            ErrorCode::InsufficientFunds\\n        );\\n        \\n        account.balance = account.balance\\n            .checked_sub(amount)\\n            .ok_or(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n        \\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct ProcessTransaction<'info> {\\n    #[account(\\n        mut,\\n        has_one = authority,  // Validated on-chain\\n    )]\\n    pub user_account: Account<'info, UserAccount>,\\n    pub authority: Signer<'info>,  // Must be signer on-chain\\n}\\n\\n#[account]\\npub struct UserAccount {\\n    pub authority: Pubkey,\\n    pub balance: u64,\\n}\\n\\n#[error_code]\\npub enum ErrorCode {\\n    #[msg(\\"Insufficient funds\\")]\\n    InsufficientFunds,\\n    #[msg(\\"Arithmetic overflow\\")]\\n    ArithmeticOverflow,\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/api/http#simulatetransaction", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/clients/jsonrpc-api#simulatetransaction"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.564553+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.043567+00	t
BVD-SOLIDITY-AA-001	Account Abstraction Vulnerability	Vulnerabilities in ERC-4337 Account Abstraction implementation including EntryPoint trust issues, paymaster abuse, signature aggregation bypasses, and session key exploits	account-abstraction	critical	SWC-XXX	CWE-284	A1: Access Control	Implement proper EntryPoint validation, secure paymaster logic with rate limiting, validate signature aggregation properly, and enforce secure session key management	["Validate EntryPoint trust and authorization", "Implement paymaster abuse prevention with rate limiting", "Secure signature aggregation with proper validation", "Enforce session key expiration and proper access controls"]	["https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-4337", "https://www.erc4337.io/docs/security"]	{static,manual}	0.15	{solidity}	Account Abstraction implementations that fail to properly validate EntryPoint operations, paymaster authorization, signature aggregation, or session key management	{"account abstraction",erc-4337,entrypoint,paymaster,bundler,"user operation"}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.661978+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.141059+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-ACC-009	Unvalidated Account Data	Account data used without confirming its authenticity or integrity. In Solana's account model, programs receive raw account data that could be from any source. Without validation of account ownership, discriminators, or data structure, programs may process malicious or corrupted data leading to unauthorized state changes, fund theft, or program compromise. This is broader than just discriminator validation - it includes all forms of account data validation.	account-validation	high	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Implement comprehensive account validation: verify ownership, validate discriminators, check data structure integrity, and validate relationships between accounts. Use Anchor's account constraints for automatic validation.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: No account validation\\nuse borsh::BorshDeserialize;\\n\\npub fn process_transfer(\\n    from_account: &AccountInfo,\\n    to_account: &AccountInfo,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Directly deserialize without any checks!\\n    let from = UserAccount::try_from_slice(&from_account.data.borrow())?;\\n    let to = UserAccount::try_from_slice(&to_account.data.borrow())?;\\n    \\n    // Process without validating accounts are legitimate\\n    transfer(from, to, amount)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Partial validation\\npub fn process_payment(\\n    payer: &AccountInfo,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Only checks if signer, but doesn't validate data\\n    if !payer.is_signer {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::MissingRequiredSignature);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // No data validation before use\\n    let account = UserAccount::try_from_slice(&payer.data.borrow())?;\\n    process_payment_internal(account, amount)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Comprehensive validation\\npub fn process_transfer(\\n    program_id: &Pubkey,\\n    from_account: &AccountInfo,\\n    to_account: &AccountInfo,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // 1. Validate ownership\\n    if from_account.owner != program_id {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::IncorrectProgramId);\\n    }\\n    if to_account.owner != program_id {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::IncorrectProgramId);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // 2. Validate data size\\n    if from_account.data_len() < UserAccount::LEN {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidAccountData);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // 3. Validate discriminator\\n    let from_data = from_account.data.borrow();\\n    if &from_data[0..8] != UserAccount::DISCRIMINATOR {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidAccountData);\\n    }\\n    \\n    // 4. Deserialize after validation\\n    let from = UserAccount::try_from_slice(&from_data[8..])?;\\n    \\n    // Repeat for to_account...\\n    let to_data = to_account.data.borrow();\\n    if &to_data[0..8] != UserAccount::DISCRIMINATOR {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidAccountData);\\n    }\\n    let to = UserAccount::try_from_slice(&to_data[8..])?;\\n    \\n    // 5. Validate account relationships\\n    if from.authority != to.authority {\\n        // Additional business logic validation\\n    }\\n    \\n    transfer_internal(from, to, amount)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor (automatic validation)\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct ProcessTransfer<'info> {\\n    #[account(\\n        mut,\\n        has_one = authority,  // Validates authority field\\n        constraint = from.balance >= amount @ ErrorCode::InsufficientFunds\\n    )]\\n    pub from: Account<'info, UserAccount>,  // Validates ownership + discriminator\\n    \\n    #[account(\\n        mut,\\n        constraint = from.key() != to.key() @ ErrorCode::SameAccount\\n    )]\\n    pub to: Account<'info, UserAccount>,  // Validates ownership + discriminator\\n    \\n    pub authority: Signer<'info>,  // Validates signer\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_transfer(\\n    ctx: Context<ProcessTransfer>,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> Result<()> {\\n    // All validation performed by Anchor automatically:\\n    // - Account ownership\\n    // - Discriminators\\n    // - Signer verification\\n    // - Custom constraints\\n    \\n    let from = &mut ctx.accounts.from;\\n    let to = &mut ctx.accounts.to;\\n    \\n    from.balance = from.balance\\n        .checked_sub(amount)\\n        .ok_or(ErrorCode::ArithmeticError)?;\\n    \\n    to.balance = to.balance\\n        .checked_add(amount)\\n        .ok_or(ErrorCode::ArithmeticError)?;\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n#[account]\\npub struct UserAccount {\\n    pub authority: Pubkey,\\n    pub balance: u64,\\n}\\n\\nconst DISCRIMINATOR: [u8; 8] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8];\\nimpl UserAccount {\\n    pub const LEN: usize = 8 + 32 + 8;  // discriminator + pubkey + u64\\n    pub const DISCRIMINATOR: &'static [u8] = &DISCRIMINATOR;\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/accounts", "https://www.anchor-lang.com/docs/account-constraints"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.597047+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.076461+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-ARI-001	Felt252 Unsafe Arithmetic Operations	The felt252 type in Cairo is not overflow/underflow safe. Unlike u256 or u128, felt252 operations wrap around modulo the Cairo prime (2^251 + 17 * 2^192 + 1) without raising errors. When user-controlled values are used in felt252 arithmetic without bounds checking, attackers can exploit wraparound behavior to manipulate calculations, bypass validations, or drain funds.	arithmetic	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use unsigned integer types (u8, u16, u32, u64, u128, u256) instead of felt252 for arithmetic operations. These types have built-in overflow/underflow checks. If felt252 is necessary, implement explicit bounds checking before operations. For financial calculations, always use u256 or implement safe math libraries.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: felt252 arithmetic without bounds checking\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn transfer(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: felt252) {\\n    let sender_balance: felt252 = self.balances.read(get_caller_address());\\n    // Subtraction can underflow, addition can overflow\\n    let new_sender_balance = sender_balance - amount;\\n    let recipient_balance = self.balances.read(recipient);\\n    let new_recipient_balance = recipient_balance + amount;\\n    \\n    self.balances.write(get_caller_address(), new_sender_balance);\\n    self.balances.write(recipient, new_recipient_balance);\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Use u256 with automatic checks\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn transfer(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    let sender = get_caller_address();\\n    let sender_balance: u256 = self.balances.read(sender);\\n    \\n    // These operations automatically check for overflow/underflow\\n    assert(sender_balance >= amount, 'Insufficient balance');\\n    self.balances.write(sender, sender_balance - amount);\\n    \\n    let recipient_balance = self.balances.read(recipient);\\n    self.balances.write(recipient, recipient_balance + amount);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Felt252 Unsafe Arithmetic"}, {"url": "https://oxor.io/blog/2024-08-16-overflow-and-underflow-vulnerabilities-in-cairo/", "title": "Cairo Overflow and Underflow Vulnerabilities"}, {"url": "https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch02-02-data-types.html", "title": "Cairo Field Elements"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.610091+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.092383+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-REE-002	Read-Only Reentrancy	Read-only reentrancy occurs in view functions that read storage variables that can be modified by external calls in other functions. When a view function reads state after an external call in a non-view function, it may return stale or inconsistent data. This can be exploited in DeFi protocols where price oracles, collateral ratios, or other critical values are queried while the contract is in an inconsistent state.	reentrancy	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Implement reentrancy guards even for view functions that read critical state. Ensure state consistency before allowing external contracts to query values. Use snapshots or checkpoints for values that must remain consistent during execution. Consider using the OpenZeppelin ReentrancyGuard for all state-reading functions in sensitive contexts.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: View function reading inconsistent state\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_oracle(ref self: ContractState) {\\n    let old_price = self.price.read();\\n    // External call that could re-enter\\n    let new_price = IOracleDispatcher { contract_address: self.oracle.read() }\\n        .get_price();\\n    self.price.write(new_price);\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_collateral_ratio(self: @ContractState, user: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    let price = self.price.read(); // May read stale price during reentrancy\\n    let collateral = self.collateral.read(user);\\n    collateral * price / PRECISION\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Reentrancy guard for state consistency\\nuse openzeppelin::security::reentrancyguard::ReentrancyGuardComponent;\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_oracle(ref self: ContractState) {\\n    self.reentrancy_guard.start();\\n    let old_price = self.price.read();\\n    let new_price = IOracleDispatcher { contract_address: self.oracle.read() }\\n        .get_price();\\n    self.price.write(new_price);\\n    self.reentrancy_guard.end();\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_collateral_ratio(self: @ContractState, user: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    assert(!self.reentrancy_guard.is_active(), 'Reentrancy detected');\\n    let price = self.price.read();\\n    let collateral = self.collateral.read(user);\\n    collateral * price / PRECISION\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Read-Only Reentrancy"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/immunefi/read-only-reentrancy-a-deep-dive-8ea3dbe5f275", "title": "Read-Only Reentrancy in DeFi"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.621059+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.104073+00	t
