BVD-SOLANA-ACC-006	Unvalidated Sysvar Accounts	System variable (sysvar) accounts used without proper validation. Sysvars provide access to cluster state (Clock, Rent, EpochSchedule, etc.) but programs must verify they are receiving the correct sysvar account. Passing fake sysvar accounts can manipulate program logic that depends on blockchain state.	account-validation	medium	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Validate sysvar account addresses against known sysvar IDs before use. Use the sysvar::* modules' ID constants for validation.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: No sysvar validation\\nuse solana_program::clock::Clock;\\n\\npub fn process(\\n    accounts: &[AccountInfo],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let clock_account = &accounts[0];\\n    let clock = Clock::from_account_info(clock_account)?;\\n    // Use clock without validation\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Validate sysvar account\\nuse solana_program::{\\n    clock::Clock,\\n    sysvar::{self, Sysvar},\\n};\\n\\npub fn process(\\n    accounts: &[AccountInfo],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let clock_account = &accounts[0];\\n    \\n    // Validate this is the real Clock sysvar\\n    if clock_account.key != &sysvar::clock::id() {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument);\\n    }\\n    \\n    let clock = Clock::from_account_info(clock_account)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Use Sysvar::get() (recommended)\\npub fn process() -> ProgramResult {\\n    let clock = Clock::get()?;\\n    // clock is guaranteed to be from the real sysvar\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/developing/runtime-facilities/sysvars", "https://docs.rs/solana-program/latest/solana_program/sysvar/index.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.509987+00	2025-12-24 02:14:18.969938+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-TYP-003	Enum Variant Confusion	Type confusion in enum deserialization where programs don't properly validate enum discriminants, allowing invalid or unexpected variants to be processed. In Borsh serialization, enums are prefixed with a variant index, but missing validation can allow out-of-range indices or mismatched variants.	type-safety	medium	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Use Rust's type system and Borsh's built-in validation. Avoid manual enum deserialization. Use match statements with explicit patterns and no wildcards for critical logic.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unsafe enum handling\\n#[derive(BorshDeserialize, BorshSerialize)]\\npub enum InstructionType {\\n    Initialize = 0,\\n    Deposit = 1,\\n    Withdraw = 2,\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_instruction(\\n    instruction_data: &[u8],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Borsh deserializes any u8 into the enum\\n    // Value 255 would panic or create invalid variant\\n    let instruction_type = InstructionType::try_from_slice(instruction_data)?;\\n    \\n    // Wildcard catches invalid variants silently\\n    match instruction_type {\\n        InstructionType::Initialize => initialize()?,\\n        _ => {}\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Manual enum parsing\\npub fn parse_instruction_type(data: &[u8]) -> InstructionType {\\n    // No validation of variant value\\n    let variant = data[0];\\n    unsafe { std::mem::transmute::<u8, InstructionType>(variant) }\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Explicit variant matching\\n#[derive(BorshDeserialize, BorshSerialize, PartialEq, Debug)]\\npub enum InstructionType {\\n    Initialize,\\n    Deposit,\\n    Withdraw,\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_instruction(\\n    instruction_data: &[u8],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let instruction_type = InstructionType::try_from_slice(instruction_data)\\n        .map_err(|_| ProgramError::InvalidInstructionData)?;\\n    \\n    // Explicit match with no wildcards\\n    match instruction_type {\\n        InstructionType::Initialize => initialize()?,\\n        InstructionType::Deposit => deposit()?,\\n        InstructionType::Withdraw => withdraw()?,\\n        // Compiler ensures all variants handled\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor's instruction enum\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[program]\\npub mod my_program {\\n    use super::*;\\n    \\n    pub fn initialize(ctx: Context<Initialize>) -> Result<()> {\\n        // Anchor validates instruction discriminator\\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n    \\n    pub fn deposit(ctx: Context<Deposit>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n        // Each instruction has unique discriminator\\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n    \\n    pub fn withdraw(ctx: Context<Withdraw>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Validated enum with Try trait\\nuse std::convert::TryFrom;\\n\\n#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]\\npub enum TransactionStatus {\\n    Pending = 0,\\n    Completed = 1,\\n    Failed = 2,\\n}\\n\\nimpl TryFrom<u8> for TransactionStatus {\\n    type Error = ProgramError;\\n    \\n    fn try_from(value: u8) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {\\n        match value {\\n            0 => Ok(TransactionStatus::Pending),\\n            1 => Ok(TransactionStatus::Completed),\\n            2 => Ok(TransactionStatus::Failed),\\n            _ => Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument),\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_status(status_byte: u8) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let status = TransactionStatus::try_from(status_byte)?;\\n    // status is guaranteed to be valid variant\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://borsh.io/", "https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch06-01-defining-an-enum.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.561826+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.040632+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-LOG-001	Incorrect Loop Termination Logic	Loops with flawed break conditions, unreachable exits, or incorrect iteration logic that can cause infinite loops, incomplete processing, or incorrect state updates. In Solana programs with compute unit limits, infinite loops will exhaust the budget and cause transaction failure, but incorrect loop logic can also lead to partial state updates or skipped validation.	logic-errors	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Ensure loop conditions are correct and reachable. Use bounded loops with explicit limits. Validate loop invariants and ensure all items are processed correctly.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unreachable break condition\\npub fn process_items(items: &[Item]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let mut i = 0;\\n    loop {\\n        if i >= items.len() {\\n            break;  // Correct condition\\n        }\\n        \\n        process_item(&items[i])?;\\n        \\n        // MISSING: i increment - infinite loop!\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Off-by-one error\\npub fn distribute_rewards(users: &mut [User], total: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let per_user = total / users.len() as u64;\\n    \\n    // Skips last user!\\n    for i in 0..users.len() - 1 {\\n        users[i].balance += per_user;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Early break skips validation\\npub fn validate_accounts(accounts: &[AccountInfo]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    for account in accounts {\\n        if !account.is_signer {\\n            break;  // Should be 'continue' or 'return Err'\\n        }\\n        // Later accounts not validated!\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct loop with bounds\\npub fn process_items(items: &[Item]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Use iterator with explicit bound\\n    for item in items.iter() {\\n        process_item(item)?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_items_indexed(items: &[Item]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Explicit iteration with correct bounds\\n    for i in 0..items.len() {\\n        process_item(&items[i])?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct distribution logic\\npub fn distribute_rewards(users: &mut [User], total: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let user_count = users.len() as u64;\\n    require!(user_count > 0, ErrorCode::NoUsers);\\n    \\n    let per_user = total.checked_div(user_count)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    // Process all users\\n    for user in users.iter_mut() {\\n        user.balance = user.balance\\n            .checked_add(per_user)\\n            .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Complete validation\\npub fn validate_accounts(accounts: &[AccountInfo]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    for account in accounts {\\n        if !account.is_signer {\\n            return Err(ProgramError::MissingRequiredSignature);\\n        }\\n        // All accounts validated before continuing\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with bounded loops\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn process_batch(\\n    ctx: Context<ProcessBatch>,\\n    items: Vec<u64>,\\n) -> Result<()> {\\n    // Validate size limit\\n    const MAX_BATCH_SIZE: usize = 10;\\n    require!(\\n        items.len() <= MAX_BATCH_SIZE,\\n        ErrorCode::BatchTooLarge\\n    );\\n    \\n    // Process with guaranteed bound\\n    for item in items.iter() {\\n        process_item_safe(*item)?;\\n    }\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/runtime#compute-budget", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/on-chain-programs/limitations#compute-budget"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.569551+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.047017+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-INT-003	Integer Division Precision Loss	Integer division operations that cause precision loss in financial calculations. In Rust, division of integers truncates the fractional part, which can lead to rounding errors in token amounts, fee calculations, or reward distributions. Repeated division operations can accumulate significant errors.	arithmetic	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "For financial calculations, perform multiplication before division to minimize precision loss. Consider using fixed-point arithmetic libraries or scaling factors. Document any intentional rounding behavior.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Division before multiplication\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_rate: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // If fee_rate is a percentage (e.g., 5 for 5%)\\n    // This loses precision!\\n    (amount / 100) * fee_rate\\n}\\n\\n// Example: amount = 999, fee_rate = 5\\n// Result: (999 / 100) * 5 = 9 * 5 = 45\\n// Expected: 999 * 0.05 = 49.95 \\u2248 49\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Multiple divisions\\npub fn distribute_rewards(total: u64, users: u64) -> u64 {\\n    let per_user = total / users;  // Precision loss\\n    let per_day = per_user / 30;   // More precision loss\\n    per_day\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Multiplication before division\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_rate: u64) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // Multiply first, then divide\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_rate)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(100))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// Example: amount = 999, fee_rate = 5\\n// Result: (999 * 5) / 100 = 4995 / 100 = 49 \\u2713\\n\\n// SECURE: Using basis points (1/10000)\\npub fn calculate_fee_basis_points(amount: u64, fee_bps: u64) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // fee_bps in basis points (e.g., 500 = 5%)\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_bps)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(10000))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Fixed-point with scaling factor\\nconst SCALE: u64 = 1_000_000;  // 6 decimal places\\n\\npub fn calculate_scaled_amount(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    rate_scaled: u64,  // Rate pre-multiplied by SCALE\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(rate_scaled)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(SCALE))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with documented rounding\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_numerator: u64, fee_denominator: u64) -> Result<u64> {\\n    // Explicitly document rounding behavior\\n    let fee = amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_numerator)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(fee_denominator))\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))?;\\n    \\n    Ok(fee)  // Rounds down (floor division)\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#integer-types", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/on-chain-programs/developing-rust#precision"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.548863+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.025625+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-ACC-001	Controlled Library Call Vulnerability	Library calls using user-controlled class hashes allow attackers to redirect contract execution to malicious implementations. In Cairo/Starknet, library calls execute code from another contract's class using its class hash. If the class hash is derived from user input without validation, an attacker can supply a malicious contract's class hash, leading to arbitrary code execution within the calling contract's context.	access-control	high	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Always validate library call class hashes against a whitelist of approved contracts. Never derive class hashes directly from user input. Use hardcoded or admin-controlled class hashes for library calls.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: User-controlled library call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn execute_library_call(ref self: ContractState, class_hash: ClassHash, selector: felt252) {\\n    library_call_syscall(class_hash, selector, array![].span()).unwrap();\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Whitelist validation\\n#[storage]\\nstruct Storage {\\n    approved_libraries: LegacyMap<ClassHash, bool>,\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn execute_library_call(ref self: ContractState, class_hash: ClassHash, selector: felt252) {\\n    assert(self.approved_libraries.read(class_hash), 'Unauthorized library');\\n    library_call_syscall(class_hash, selector, array![].span()).unwrap();\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Controlled Library Call"}, {"url": "https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/architecture_and_concepts/Smart_Contracts/class-hash/", "title": "Starknet Contract Classes"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.601256+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.079941+00	t
