BVD-SOLANA-ACC-002	Account Data Reallocation Vulnerability	Improper reassignment of account resources where account data is reallocated without proper validation or cleanup. In Solana, accounts can be resized using realloc, but improper handling can lead to data corruption, loss of lamports, or unauthorized state changes. This vulnerability occurs when reallocation doesn't properly validate ownership, check size constraints, or handle existing data.	account-validation	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Validate account ownership and implement proper size checks before reallocating account data. Ensure existing data is properly handled during reallocation.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unchecked reallocation\\naccount.realloc(new_size, false)?;\\n\\n// SECURE: Validate before reallocation\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn reallocate_account(ctx: Context<ReallocateAccounts>, new_size: usize) -> Result<()> {\\n    let account = &ctx.accounts.my_account.to_account_info();\\n    \\n    // Validate ownership\\n    require!(account.owner == ctx.program_id, ErrorCode::InvalidOwner);\\n    \\n    // Validate size constraints\\n    require!(new_size >= MIN_SIZE && new_size <= MAX_SIZE, ErrorCode::InvalidSize);\\n    \\n    // Check rent exemption\\n    let rent = Rent::get()?;\\n    let new_minimum_balance = rent.minimum_balance(new_size);\\n    require!(account.lamports() >= new_minimum_balance, ErrorCode::InsufficientFunds);\\n    \\n    account.realloc(new_size, false)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/accounts#realloc", "https://github.com/coral-xyz/anchor/discussions/2046"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.492222+00	2025-12-24 02:14:18.955404+00	t
BVD-SOLIDITY-TOKEN-SUPPLY-001	Token Supply Manipulation	Token supply manipulation vulnerabilities including front-running of permit functions and unauthorized supply changes	token	high	SWC-XXX	CWE-362	A4: Race Conditions	Implement proper access controls on mint/burn functions, protect permit functions from front-running, use nonces for permits, and validate supply changes	["Use onlyOwner or onlyMinter for supply changes", "Implement permit deadline validation", "Use unique nonces for each permit", "Add maximum supply caps where appropriate"]	["https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-2612", "https://www.trust-security.xyz/post/permission-denied"]	{static}	0.2	{solidity}	Token contracts vulnerable to supply manipulation through unauthorized minting or permit front-running	{"token supply",permit,front-running,mint,burn}	2025-12-24 02:12:44.937369+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.224567+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-CPI-001	Arbitrary Cross-Program Invocation	Unrestricted cross-program invocations (CPI) where programs accept arbitrary program IDs without validation. In Solana, CPI allows programs to call other programs, but without proper validation, malicious programs can be invoked instead of legitimate ones. This can lead to unauthorized state changes, fund theft, or complete program compromise.	cross-program-invocation	critical	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Always validate that CPI target program IDs match expected addresses. Use hardcoded program IDs or verify against known addresses before invoking.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Arbitrary CPI target\\nuse solana_program::program::invoke;\\n\\npub fn process(\\n    accounts: &[AccountInfo],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let target_program = &accounts[0];\\n    \\n    // No validation - can call ANY program!\\n    invoke(\\n        &instruction,\\n        &[target_program.clone()],\\n    )?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Validate CPI target\\nuse solana_program::program::invoke;\\nuse spl_token::id as token_program_id;\\n\\npub fn process(\\n    accounts: &[AccountInfo],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let target_program = &accounts[0];\\n    \\n    // Validate program ID before CPI\\n    if target_program.key != &token_program_id() {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::IncorrectProgramId);\\n    }\\n    \\n    invoke(\\n        &instruction,\\n        &[target_program.clone()],\\n    )?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with explicit program constraint\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\nuse anchor_spl::token::{Token, TokenAccount};\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct TransferTokens<'info> {\\n    #[account(mut)]\\n    pub from: Account<'info, TokenAccount>,\\n    #[account(mut)]\\n    pub to: Account<'info, TokenAccount>,\\n    pub authority: Signer<'info>,\\n    // Anchor validates this is the SPL Token program\\n    pub token_program: Program<'info, Token>,\\n}\\n\\npub fn transfer_tokens(ctx: Context<TransferTokens>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n    // CPI target is guaranteed to be SPL Token program\\n    token::transfer(\\n        CpiContext::new(\\n            ctx.accounts.token_program.to_account_info(),\\n            Transfer {\\n                from: ctx.accounts.from.to_account_info(),\\n                to: ctx.accounts.to.to_account_info(),\\n                authority: ctx.accounts.authority.to_account_info(),\\n            },\\n        ),\\n        amount,\\n    )?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://github.com/coral-xyz/sealevel-attacks/tree/master/programs/8-arbitrary-cpi", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/calling-between-programs"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.518966+00	2025-12-24 02:14:18.983247+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-CPI-002	Duplicate Mutable Accounts in CPI	Mutable accounts passed multiple times in instruction account lists, enabling double-spend and state manipulation attacks. When the same account is provided as two different mutable references, the program can modify it multiple times in ways that violate invariants, such as withdrawing funds twice from the same account.	cross-program-invocation	critical	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Validate that mutable accounts are unique before processing. Check account keys to ensure no duplicates exist in critical operations.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: No duplicate check\\npub fn transfer_between(\\n    from: &AccountInfo,\\n    to: &AccountInfo,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // If from == to, double the amount!\\n    **from.lamports.borrow_mut() -= amount;\\n    **to.lamports.borrow_mut() += amount;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Validate accounts are different\\npub fn transfer_between(\\n    from: &AccountInfo,\\n    to: &AccountInfo,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Prevent same account being passed twice\\n    if from.key == to.key {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument);\\n    }\\n    \\n    **from.lamports.borrow_mut() -= amount;\\n    **to.lamports.borrow_mut() += amount;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor constraint\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct Transfer<'info> {\\n    #[account(mut)]\\n    pub from: Account<'info, TokenAccount>,\\n    #[account(\\n        mut,\\n        constraint = from.key() != to.key() @ ErrorCode::DuplicateAccount\\n    )]\\n    pub to: Account<'info, TokenAccount>,\\n}\\n\\npub fn transfer(ctx: Context<Transfer>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n    // Accounts guaranteed to be different\\n    ctx.accounts.from.amount -= amount;\\n    ctx.accounts.to.amount += amount;\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://github.com/coral-xyz/sealevel-attacks/tree/master/programs/9-duplicate-mutable-accounts", "https://www.anchor-lang.com/docs/account-constraints"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.523458+00	2025-12-24 02:14:18.989173+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-PDA-002	Insecure PDA Seed Construction	Program Derived Addresses created with insufficiently unique or predictable seeds, allowing attackers to derive PDAs for unauthorized resources. PDA security relies on using unique, unpredictable seeds that properly scope access. Using only constant seeds or easily guessable values allows attackers to compute PDAs for other users' resources.	program-derived-address	high	\N	\N	A02:2021	{"description": "Include user-specific data (public keys) and resource identifiers in PDA seeds to ensure uniqueness. Avoid using only constant strings or sequential numbers.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Constant-only seeds\\nlet (pda, bump) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[b\\"vault\\"],  // Anyone can derive this!\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Predictable seeds\\nlet (pda, bump) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[\\n        b\\"user\\",\\n        &user_id.to_le_bytes(),  // Sequential IDs are predictable\\n    ],\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// SECURE: User-specific seeds\\nlet (pda, bump) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[\\n        b\\"vault\\",\\n        authority.key().as_ref(),  // Unique per user\\n    ],\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// SECURE: Multiple unique identifiers\\nlet (pda, bump) = Pubkey::find_program_address(\\n    &[\\n        b\\"escrow\\",\\n        authority.key().as_ref(),\\n        mint.key().as_ref(),  // Unique per user + token\\n        &nonce.to_le_bytes(), // Additional uniqueness\\n    ],\\n    program_id,\\n);\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with user-specific seeds\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[derive(Accounts)]\\npub struct InitializeVault<'info> {\\n    #[account(\\n        init,\\n        payer = authority,\\n        space = 8 + Vault::INIT_SPACE,\\n        seeds = [\\n            b\\"vault\\",\\n            authority.key().as_ref(),  // User-specific\\n            mint.key().as_ref(),       // Token-specific\\n        ],\\n        bump\\n    )]\\n    pub vault: Account<'info, Vault>,\\n    pub authority: Signer<'info>,\\n    pub mint: Account<'info, Mint>,\\n    pub system_program: Program<'info, System>,\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/calling-between-programs#program-derived-addresses", "https://www.anchor-lang.com/docs/pdas#seeds"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.532585+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.002459+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-LOG-002	Incorrect Conditional Logic	Flawed conditional checks including wrong comparison operators, inverted logic, missing conditions, or incorrect boolean combinations. These errors can bypass security checks, cause incorrect state transitions, or allow unauthorized operations.	logic-errors	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Carefully review all conditional logic. Use explicit comparisons, avoid double negatives, and test boundary conditions. Use Anchor's require! macro for clear assertions.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Wrong comparison operator\\npub fn check_balance(balance: u64, minimum: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Should be >= not >\\n    if balance > minimum {\\n        return Ok(());\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::InsufficientFunds)\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Inverted logic\\npub fn authorize_withdrawal(is_authorized: bool) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Logic is inverted!\\n    if !is_authorized {\\n        return Ok(());  // Allows unauthorized users\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::Unauthorized)\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Missing condition\\npub fn validate_amount(amount: u64, min: u64, max: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Only checks minimum, not maximum!\\n    if amount >= min {\\n        return Ok(());\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::InvalidAmount)\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Wrong boolean operator\\npub fn check_permissions(is_admin: bool, is_owner: bool) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Should be OR (||) not AND (&&)\\n    // Only allows if BOTH admin AND owner\\n    if is_admin && is_owner {\\n        return Ok(());\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::Unauthorized)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct comparison\\npub fn check_balance(balance: u64, minimum: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    if balance >= minimum {\\n        return Ok(());\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::InsufficientFunds)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct logic flow\\npub fn authorize_withdrawal(is_authorized: bool) -> ProgramResult {\\n    if is_authorized {\\n        return Ok(());\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::Unauthorized)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Complete validation\\npub fn validate_amount(amount: u64, min: u64, max: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    if amount < min {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::AmountTooLow);\\n    }\\n    if amount > max {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::AmountTooHigh);\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct boolean logic\\npub fn check_permissions(is_admin: bool, is_owner: bool) -> ProgramResult {\\n    if is_admin || is_owner {\\n        return Ok(());\\n    }\\n    Err(ProgramError::Unauthorized)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor require! macro\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn withdraw(\\n    ctx: Context<Withdraw>,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> Result<()> {\\n    let account = &ctx.accounts.user_account;\\n    \\n    // Clear, explicit assertions\\n    require!(\\n        account.balance >= amount,\\n        ErrorCode::InsufficientFunds\\n    );\\n    \\n    require!(\\n        amount >= MIN_WITHDRAWAL,\\n        ErrorCode::AmountTooLow\\n    );\\n    \\n    require!(\\n        amount <= MAX_WITHDRAWAL,\\n        ErrorCode::AmountTooHigh\\n    );\\n    \\n    require!(\\n        account.is_active,\\n        ErrorCode::AccountInactive\\n    );\\n    \\n    // Process withdrawal\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-05-control-flow.html", "https://www.anchor-lang.com/docs/errors"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.572137+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.050818+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-INT-001	Unchecked Arithmetic Operations	Arithmetic operations performed without overflow/underflow checks in Solana Rust programs. While Rust has built-in overflow checking in debug mode, release builds use wrapping arithmetic by default. Programs must explicitly use checked arithmetic methods to prevent integer overflow/underflow vulnerabilities that can lead to incorrect calculations, unauthorized minting, or fund theft.	arithmetic	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use checked arithmetic methods (checked_add, checked_sub, checked_mul, checked_div) that return Option<T> and handle None cases. Never unwrap() results without validation.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unchecked arithmetic\\npub fn deposit(account: &mut Account, amount: u64) {\\n    // Can overflow in release mode!\\n    account.balance = account.balance + amount;\\n}\\n\\npub fn withdraw(account: &mut Account, amount: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Can underflow!\\n    account.balance = account.balance - amount;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Unwrapping checked operations\\npub fn deposit_unwrap(account: &mut Account, amount: u64) {\\n    // Panics on overflow instead of returning error!\\n    account.balance = account.balance.checked_add(amount).unwrap();\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Proper checked arithmetic\\npub fn deposit(account: &mut Account, amount: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    account.balance = account.balance\\n        .checked_add(amount)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::Arithmetic overflow)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\npub fn withdraw(account: &mut Account, amount: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    account.balance = account.balance\\n        .checked_sub(amount)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::InsufficientFunds)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor (automatic overflow checks)\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[account]\\npub struct UserAccount {\\n    pub balance: u64,\\n}\\n\\npub fn deposit(ctx: Context<Deposit>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n    let account = &mut ctx.accounts.user_account;\\n    \\n    // Anchor's require! macro for validation\\n    account.balance = account.balance\\n        .checked_add(amount)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))?;\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\npub fn withdraw(ctx: Context<Withdraw>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n    let account = &mut ctx.accounts.user_account;\\n    \\n    account.balance = account.balance\\n        .checked_sub(amount)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::InsufficientFunds))?;\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#integer-overflow", "https://docs.rs/solana-program/latest/solana_program/macro.checked_add.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.542175+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.015844+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-INT-002	Unsafe Saturating Arithmetic	Inappropriate use of saturating arithmetic (saturating_add, saturating_sub, saturating_mul) in contexts where overflow/underflow should be an error. Saturating arithmetic silently clamps values at numeric boundaries instead of failing, which can mask critical errors in financial calculations, access control, or state transitions.	arithmetic	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use saturating arithmetic only when saturation is the intended behavior (e.g., calculating rewards caps). For financial operations, always use checked arithmetic that returns errors.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Saturating arithmetic in financial operations\\npub fn transfer(from: &mut Account, to: &mut Account, amount: u64) {\\n    // Silently fails if from.balance < amount!\\n    from.balance = from.balance.saturating_sub(amount);\\n    to.balance = to.balance.saturating_add(amount);\\n    // User loses funds without error\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Saturating in access control\\npub fn consume_credits(user: &mut User, cost: u64) -> bool {\\n    user.credits = user.credits.saturating_sub(cost);\\n    // Always returns true even if insufficient credits!\\n    true\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Checked arithmetic for financial operations\\npub fn transfer(\\n    from: &mut Account,\\n    to: &mut Account,\\n    amount: u64,\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    from.balance = from.balance\\n        .checked_sub(amount)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::InsufficientFunds)?;\\n    \\n    to.balance = to.balance\\n        .checked_add(amount)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Checked arithmetic for access control\\npub fn consume_credits(user: &mut User, cost: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    user.credits = user.credits\\n        .checked_sub(cost)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::InsufficientCredits)?;\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// ACCEPTABLE: Saturating for capped rewards\\npub fn calculate_reward_with_cap(base: u64, multiplier: u64, cap: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Saturating is OK here - we want to cap at maximum\\n    let reward = base.saturating_mul(multiplier);\\n    reward.min(cap)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn transfer(ctx: Context<Transfer>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n    let from = &mut ctx.accounts.from;\\n    let to = &mut ctx.accounts.to;\\n    \\n    from.balance = from.balance\\n        .checked_sub(amount)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::InsufficientFunds))?;\\n    \\n    to.balance = to.balance\\n        .checked_add(amount)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))?;\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/primitive.u64.html#method.saturating_add", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/on-chain-programs/developing-rust#arithmetic"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.544885+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.021694+00	t
BVD-SOLIDITY-LOGIC-001	Logic Error Vulnerability	Logic errors including invalid state transitions, incorrect business logic implementation, and parameter inconsistencies	logic	high	SWC-XXX	CWE-840	A3: Logic Errors	Implement comprehensive unit tests, use formal verification for critical logic, add state transition validation, and conduct thorough code reviews	["Add state machine validation with require statements", "Implement comprehensive unit and integration tests", "Use formal verification tools (Certora, etc.)", "Add invariant checks throughout contract"]	["https://github.com/crytic/building-secure-contracts/blob/master/program-analysis/echidna/basic/common-testing-approaches.md"]	{manual,fuzzing,formal}	0.3	{solidity}	Contracts with incorrect business logic or invalid state transition handling	{"logic error","state transition","business logic"}	2025-12-24 02:12:44.934096+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.221459+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-L2S-001	Unchecked L1 Handler Origin	L1 message handlers that don't validate the sender address on L1 can be exploited by malicious L1 contracts. Starknet allows L1 Ethereum contracts to send messages to L2 Cairo contracts via L1 handlers. Without validating the from_address parameter, any L1 contract can trigger the handler, potentially bypassing intended access controls or injecting malicious data.	layer2-security	high	\N	\N	A07:2021	{"description": "Always validate the from_address parameter in L1 handlers against a whitelist of authorized L1 contracts. Store approved L1 addresses in storage and check them before processing messages. Use the #[l1_handler] attribute correctly and implement strict origin validation.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: No L1 origin validation\\n#[l1_handler]\\nfn process_l1_message(ref self: ContractState, from_address: felt252, amount: u256) {\\n    // Any L1 contract can send this message\\n    self.balance.write(self.balance.read() + amount);\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: L1 origin validation\\n#[storage]\\nstruct Storage {\\n    authorized_l1_bridge: felt252,\\n    balance: u256,\\n}\\n\\n#[l1_handler]\\nfn process_l1_message(ref self: ContractState, from_address: felt252, amount: u256) {\\n    assert(from_address == self.authorized_l1_bridge.read(), 'Unauthorized L1 sender');\\n    self.balance.write(self.balance.read() + amount);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Unchecked L1 Handler"}, {"url": "https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/architecture_and_concepts/L1-L2_Communication/messaging-mechanism/", "title": "Starknet L1-L2 Messaging"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.607051+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.088494+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-STA-001	Unenforced View Function Constraint	Functions decorated with #[view] or marked as view are intended to be read-only and should not modify contract state. However, Cairo compiler doesn't strictly enforce this constraint. If a view function modifies storage or calls non-view external functions, it violates the expected behavior and can lead to unexpected state changes during what should be read-only operations.	state-consistency	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Ensure view functions only read state and never write to storage. Avoid calling external functions from view functions unless those functions are also guaranteed to be view. Use read-only storage access patterns. Consider using @view decorator in Cairo 0 or proper view semantics in Cairo 1/2.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: View function modifying state\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_balance(self: @ContractState, account: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    let balance = self.balances.read(account);\\n    // View function should not write!\\n    self.last_query_time.write(get_block_timestamp());\\n    balance\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Pure read-only view function\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_balance(self: @ContractState, account: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    self.balances.read(account)\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Unenforced View"}, {"url": "https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch99-01-02-a-simple-contract.html", "title": "Cairo External Functions"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.612523+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.095622+00	t
BVD-SOLIDITY-EIP7702-001	EIP-7702 Account Delegation Vulnerability	Critical vulnerabilities in EIP-7702 account delegation including malicious sweeper contracts (97% of 2025 delegations), initialization front-running ($1.54M exploit), batch phishing, and tx.origin bypasses	delegation	critical	SWC-115	CWE-269	A1: Access Control	Implement sweeper contract verification, protect initialization with proper access controls and checks-effects-interactions, validate batch operations, and avoid tx.origin for authentication	["Verify delegation target is not a malicious sweeper", "Protect initialization with owner-only modifier and reentrancy guard", "Validate all operations in batch transactions", "Use msg.sender instead of tx.origin for authentication"]	["https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7702", "https://github.com/ethereum/EIPs/blob/master/EIPS/eip-7702.md"]	{static,manual}	0.1	{solidity}	Account delegation contracts that fail to validate delegation targets, protect initialization, or properly authenticate delegated operations	{eip-7702,delegation,sweeper,"account takeover","init front-run"}	2025-12-24 02:12:44.798344+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.143468+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-REE-003	Benign Reentrancy	Benign reentrancy occurs when a storage variable is written after an external call but was not read before it. While not immediately exploitable, benign reentrancy indicates potential issues with state consistency and can become critical if the code evolves to read the variable before the call. It also increases code complexity and makes future modifications more dangerous.	reentrancy	low	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Follow the checks-effects-interactions pattern consistently even when current code doesn't read the variable. Move all state updates before external calls. This prevents future modifications from inadvertently introducing vulnerabilities. Use reentrancy guards as a defense-in-depth measure.", "code_example": "// BENIGN BUT RISKY: State update after external call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn process_payment(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    // External call first\\n    IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: self.token.read() }\\n        .transfer(recipient, amount);\\n    \\n    // State update after (benign if not read before, but risky pattern)\\n    self.total_processed.write(self.total_processed.read() + amount);\\n}\\n\\n// BETTER: State update before external call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn process_payment(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    // Update state first\\n    self.total_processed.write(self.total_processed.read() + amount);\\n    \\n    // External call after\\n    IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: self.token.read() }\\n        .transfer(recipient, amount);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Benign Reentrancy"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.625636+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.106683+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-REE-004	Reentrancy Affecting Events	Events emitted after external calls can lead to out-of-order or misleading event logs. When an external call allows reentrancy, events emitted after the call may appear in the wrong sequence relative to state changes. This can cause off-chain systems, indexers, and frontends to display incorrect information or process events in the wrong order, leading to user confusion or system inconsistencies.	reentrancy	low	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Emit all events before making external calls to ensure correct event ordering. Follow the pattern: checks, effects (including event emission), interactions. This ensures that events accurately reflect the state changes and appear in the correct chronological order in the event log.", "code_example": "// PROBLEMATIC: Event after external call\\n#[derive(Drop, starknet::Event)]\\nstruct Transfer {\\n    from: ContractAddress,\\n    to: ContractAddress,\\n    amount: u256,\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn transfer_with_callback(ref self: ContractState, to: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    let from = get_caller_address();\\n    self.balances.write(from, self.balances.read(from) - amount);\\n    self.balances.write(to, self.balances.read(to) + amount);\\n    \\n    // External call\\n    IReceiverDispatcher { contract_address: to }.on_receive(amount);\\n    \\n    // Event emitted after (can be out of order if re-entered)\\n    self.emit(Transfer { from, to, amount });\\n}\\n\\n// BETTER: Event before external call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn transfer_with_callback(ref self: ContractState, to: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    let from = get_caller_address();\\n    self.balances.write(from, self.balances.read(from) - amount);\\n    self.balances.write(to, self.balances.read(to) + amount);\\n    \\n    // Emit event before external call\\n    self.emit(Transfer { from, to, amount });\\n    \\n    // External call after\\n    IReceiverDispatcher { contract_address: to }.on_receive(amount);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Reentrancy Events"}, {"url": "https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch99-02-02-contract-events.html", "title": "Starknet Events"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.628908+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.109332+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-QUA-002	Unchecked Return Values	Ignoring return values from function calls, especially external calls, can lead to silent failures and incorrect assumptions about operation success. Many Cairo functions return Result types or option values that indicate success or failure. Not checking these values means errors go unnoticed, potentially leading to state inconsistencies, fund loss, or security vulnerabilities.	code-quality	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Always check return values from function calls, especially external calls and system calls. Use proper error handling with Result types. Propagate errors appropriately using the ? operator or explicit matching. For functions that can fail, always verify success before proceeding.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Ignoring return value\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn execute_transfer(ref self: ContractState, token: ContractAddress, to: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    // Return value ignored - transfer might fail silently\\n    IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: token }.transfer(to, amount);\\n    self.transfer_count.write(self.transfer_count.read() + 1);\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Check return value\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn execute_transfer(ref self: ContractState, token: ContractAddress, to: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    let success = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: token }.transfer(to, amount);\\n    assert(success, 'Transfer failed');\\n    self.transfer_count.write(self.transfer_count.read() + 1);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Unused Return"}, {"url": "https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch09-02-result.html", "title": "Cairo Error Handling"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-12-24 02:01:19.635413+00	2025-12-24 02:14:19.114709+00	t
